## Reflection

This lab made the difference between `logs`, `describe`, and `events` concrete instead of abstract. Before this, I would have reached for `kubectl logs` on any failing Pod, but seeing a container that never started (the `sleeeep` typo) return nothing from `logs` made it clear that `logs` only works once a container has actually run. Simulating a scheduling failure with a fake scheduler name was especially useful, since it's the one failure mode that produces almost no events at all, just a Pod stuck in `Pending`, which is its own kind of signal once you know to look for the missing `Scheduled` event. Working through `ImagePullBackOff` and `CrashLoopBackOff` side by side also helped me stop treating "the pod isn't working" as one problem and start recognizing it as several distinct failure categories, each with its own diagnostic path.
